<br>
1) No no-drop.  Because very very few items are flagged no-drop, it means a lot more equipment enters the economy as tradable / sellable items.  Items that on other servers would just sit on a corpse and rot find their way to the market place.  Because so much equipment is available, prices drop, and you can afford better equipment with the same amount spent.<br>
<br>
2) One char per acct.  Because people can't twink out alt characters, even more equipment ends up in the economy.  Spare platemail that might've ended up on a high level wizard's weekend warrior now ends up for sale, increasing availability and lowering prices.<br>
<br>
3) Trivial Loot Code.  Because many items collected by low level players are used in high level quests, it gives low to mid level players items of value to trade with higher end players.  If a level 50 wizard is going after her staff of temperate flux, and can't get the heart of fire anymore because TLC would destroy it, she's gonna be willing to pay quite a bit for it.<br>
<br>
4) Low server population.  Because there just aren't as many people playing here, it means there's more good items entering the economy <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> per capita</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> then on the other servers.  People can hunt the best monsters, and just let the crappy monsters sit and rot (whereas on other servers crowding would force people into the crappy areas).<br>
<br>
I think those are the main reasons.  All throughout the life of my bard I had gear above and beyond what I should've had at my level.  She had planar gear in her 30's, and post-planar gear in her 40's, all from working as a mercenary of sorts doing quests for higher level players that either took too long to bother with, or that were impossible to them due to TLC.<br>
<br>
- Syll <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uellywig.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ellywig</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 666<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/27/02 9:46:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=493.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_star.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: a question....</span><hr size=1> I would add one more reason...<br>
<br>
5) A much larger population (per capita) of slow-levelling folks who quest and tradeskill and such. Everyone isn't in some uber rush to reach some particular level, so you are far more likely to find a lower-level beastlord out there hunting hides off low blues or even greens to make themselves a full set of studded or reinforced leather armor - and trading/handing out extra practice pieces to friends and guildmates..<br>
<br>
And all that slowed levelling means a bit more self-earned cash per level than one gets from being speed-twinked. More of a mixture of cash mobs and experience mobs - rather than the pure exp rush that is more common elsewhere.<br>
<br>
